{{refimprove|date=July 2017}} {| class="infobox" width=230 |- |{{center|'''Events of years in sports'''}} |- style="background-color:#f3f3f3" |''Other years'' |- | align="center" | [[1001 to 1600 in sports|1001 to 1600]] | [[1601 to 1700 in sports|1601 to 1700]] | '''1701 to 1725''' | [[1726 to 1730 in sports|1726 to 1730]] | [[1731 to 1735 in sports|1731 to 1735]] |}
The beginning of the 18th century saw sport acquire increasing importance in the lives of people in England and Ireland. Professionalism was by then established in the major gambling sports of [[bare-knuckle boxing]], [[cricket]] and [[horse racing]].
==[[Bandy]]== '''Events''' * A game that is recognisable as modern bandy was played in Russia by the early 18th century, although the rules in use differed from those devised in England in the 1880s. In Russia, bandy is known as "hockey with a ball" or simply "Russian hockey". The game became popular among the nobility with the royal court of [[Peter I the Great]] playing bandy on [[Saint Petersburg]]'s frozen [[Neva river]]. Russians played bandy with sticks made out of juniper wood, later adopting skates.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
==[[Boxing]]== '''Events''' * 18 September 1719 — [[James Figg]] declared the first bare-knuckle boxing champion of England.<ref name="JF">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/figg-james.htm |title=James Figg |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> * 1720–23 — James Figg defeated challengers Timothy Buck, Tom Stokes, Bill Flanders and Chris Clarkson to retain the Championship of England, all the fights taking place in London.<ref name="JF"/> * 1724 — James Figg defeated by Ned Sutton at [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] for the Championship of England title, details of the fight being lost.<ref name="JF"/> * 1725 — Jack Broughton began his career with some turn-up bouts in [[Bristol]].<ref name="JB">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/broughton-jack.htm |title=Jack Broughton |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> * 31 May 1725 — Ned Sutton lost his Championship of England title in a rematch with James Figg in London. Figg retained the title until his retirement in 1730.<ref name="JF"/> * September 1725 — Jack Broughton defeated an unnamed opponent after the 10th round in one of his early fights at [[Bristol]].<ref name="JB"/>
==[[Chess]]== * By the beginning of the 18th century, France was the main centre of European chess.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
==[[Cricket]]== '''Events''' * 29 June 1709 — [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]] v [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]], the earliest known inter-county match. It was, however, probably a match between two parish teams either side of the county boundary.<ref name=FLPVC1>{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=G. B. |authorlink=G. B. Buckley |title=Fresh Light on pre-Victorian Cricket |year=1937 |publisher=Cotterell |isbn= |page=1}}</ref> * 1 September 1718 — [[London Cricket Club|London]] v [[Rochester Punch Club cricket team|Rochester Punch Club]] at [[White Conduit Fields]] was abandoned after three Rochester players made "an elopement" in an attempt to have the game declared incomplete so that they would retain their stake money. A noted lawsuit was opened by the London players in pursuance of their winnings and the judge ordered that the match be "played out".<ref name=FL18C2>{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=G. B. |authorlink=G. B. Buckley |title=Fresh Light on 18th Century Cricket |year=1935 |publisher=Cotterell |page=2}}</ref> * July 1719 — as ordered by the court, the London v Rochester match was completed and London won by 21 runs.<ref name=FL18C2/> * 1721 — mariners of the [[British East India Company]] reported to be playing cricket at [[Khambhat]] (then Cambay) in western India, the earliest known reference to cricket in the Indian sub-continent.<ref name=RG3>{{cite book |last=Guha |first=Ramachandra |authorlink=Ramachandra Guha |title=A Corner of a Foreign Field – An Indian History of a British Sport |year=2001 |publisher=Picador |isbn= |page=3}}</ref> * 1724 — earliest mention of [[Edwin Stead]], the noted [[patron (cricket)|patron]] of Kent county cricket; under his leadership, Kent was the most successful team of the 1720s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Altham |first=H. S. |authorlink=Harry Altham |title=A History of Cricket, Volume 1 (to 1914) |year=1962 |publisher=George Allen & Unwin |location=London |page=31}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Birley |first=Derek |authorlink=Derek Birley |title=A Social History of English Cricket |year=1999 |publisher=Aurum Press Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-85410-710-0 |page=19}}</ref> [[William Bedle]], described in his 1768 obituary notice as "the most expert cricket player in England", played for Kent at this time.<ref name=RB48>{{cite book |last=Bowen |first=Rowland |authorlink=Rowland Bowen |title=Cricket: A History of its Growth and Development |year=1970 |publisher=Eyre & Spottiswoode |location=London |isbn=0-413-27860-3 |page=48}}</ref><ref name=FL18C48>{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=G. B. |authorlink=G. B. Buckley |title=Fresh Light on 18th Century Cricket |year=1935 |publisher=Cotterell |page=48}}</ref> * 1725 — earliest mentions in a cricket connection of the noted [[Sussex county cricket teams|Sussex]] patrons [[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet]] and [[Charles Lennox, 2nd Duke of Richmond]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCann |first=Tim |authorlink=Timothy J. McCann |title=Sussex Cricket in the Eighteenth Century |year=2004 |publisher=Sussex Record Society |location=Lewes |isbn=0-85445-055-6 |page=4}}</ref>
==[[Curling]]== '''Events''' * 1716 — [[Kilsyth Curling Club]] was formally constituted and now claims to have been the first club in the world. Kilsyth also claims the oldest purpose-built curling pond in the world at [[Colzium]], in the form of a low dam creating a shallow pool some 100 × 250 metres in size.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paperclip.org.uk/kilsythweb/Communityresources/Curlinghistory.htm |title=Kilsyth Curling History |publisher=Paperclip.org.uk |date= |accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>
==[[Football]]== '''Ireland''' * 1712 — the earliest recorded inter-county match in Ireland at [[Slane]] between teams from [[County Louth]] and County Meath.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
==[[Horse racing]]== '''Events''' * 1711 — [[Queen Anne of England|Queen Anne]] kept a large string of racehorses and was instrumental in the organisation of racing at the village of East Cote, now known as [[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]], near [[Windsor Castle]]. She founded [[Royal Ascot]] where one of the main events each year, continuing into the 21st century, is called the [[Queen Anne Stakes]].{{fact|date=July 2017}}
==[[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]== '''Events''' * 1716 — the first race for the right to wear [[Doggett's Coat and Badge]] held among the professional watermen in London. The course runs four miles and five furlongs (7443 m) from [[London Bridge]] to [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]]. It became established as an annual event continuing into the 21st century.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
